what if we want a complete dataset (i.e., every locus X ind combination has either 1 or 8 reads?). we need to make a compromise between the number of inds and number of loci.

## 1+ read per locus * ind
dat.subset3 <- dat.subset2>=1
out <- c()
for (i in 300:351)
{
  dat.subset4 <- dat.subset2[rowSums(dat.subset3)>=i,]
  dat.subset4 <- dat.subset4[rowSums(dat.subset4>=1)>=i,] # 2nd pass
  out <- rbind(out,data.frame(ninds=i,nloci=dim(dat.subset4)[1],threshold=1))
}

## 8+ read per locus * ind
dat.subset3 <- dat.subset2>=8
for (i in 300:351)
{
  dat.subset4 <- dat.subset2[rowSums(dat.subset3)>=i,] # 1st pass of inds
  dat.subset4 <- dat.subset4[rowSums(dat.subset4>=8)>=i,] # 2nd pass
  out <- rbind(out,data.frame(ninds=i,nloci=dim(dat.subset4)[1],threshold=8))
}
print(xyplot(nloci~ninds, group=threshold,data=out,auto.key = T))

heres the set of loci and inds to use with >10K SNPs

tmp <- out[out$nloci>=10000 & out$threshold==8,]
print(to.use <- tmp[tmp$ninds==max(tmp$ninds),])
##    ninds nloci threshold
## 71   318 10064         8
dat.subset3 <- dat.subset2>=8
i=to.use$ninds
dat.subset4 <- dat.subset2[rowSums(dat.subset3)>=i,]

###filtered loci
loci <- read.delim('allloci.noMAF2.BED.txt',header=F)
loci <- loci[as.numeric(row.names(dat.subset4)),]
write.table(loci,'loci.10064.bat.out',quote=F,col.names = F,row.names = F)
